column805: 1. Communicate - PSP's website is embarrassingly inadequate. It is extremely difficult to find background documents that are supposed to be there; menus are poorly organized, outdated, and inconsistent with the organization structure; material is not updated; suggestions for how to improve this have been routinely ignored by the agency. This sends the message to the groups I work with that communication is not a priority for the Partnership. 2. Coordinate - It is difficult for organizations involved with PSP to coordinate with them when often the different parts of the agency are coordinating internally. For example, recently the PSP Monitoring Coordinator was not able to answer questions about an RFQQ sent out by another part of the PSP to coordinate monitoring. 3. Please keep calendars and agendas easily accessible and up-to-date on the website.

column805: Hyper coordination to achieve unified regional goals has the potential to collapse under too many layers of planning and prioritizing, some of which appear redundant with the many other mandated environmental resource collaborations (legislative or case law driven)in WA. In addition, hyper coordination between the local and regional levels has the potential to reward a few big actors and stifle innovations at localized levels. Our topography and micro climates are too varied for a one-size fits all solution.

column805: Name Recognition: The Partnership needs to associate value with its name and invest in promoting it. Local organizations want to promote their own names in order to survive. Website Development: Make it work. MPS is cumbersome and really doesn't make my job any easier to communicate than an email string. If it will connect visitors and new homeowners with organizations and provide a service, then I'll use it and poke around in its toolbox. Positive Accomplishment: Choose a tangible and visual measure of success, reach it and promote it. We're all "greens" here. Give us something to herald and come together to celebrate and build off of. Citizen Involvement: People want to live in Puget Sound. It's beautiful, the climate is livable and activities are plentiful. Don't crush their perception. We need to get citizens involved in what they want to do to add value to their community. Once we address what it is they value, local organizations have an idea where additional success can be met.

column805: Improve MyPugetSound.net to be a preferred resource for partners by improving its structure, functionality, number of documents you can download, etc. Currently, MyPugetSound.net is not being used by project partners because it's confusing to navigate, there are limitations to the number of documents one can upload, it doesn't always save entries, etc. It's simply not useful at this point in time. This will likely require significant revisions; however, if MyPugetSound.net is not improved, S.T.O.R.M. and other partners will likely start to search for another platform to accomplish the same goals that MyPugetSound.net was intended to achieve in the near future (which would be sad, and a waste of PSP's money). If PSP does plan to revise the site, it would be helpful for the S.T.O.R.M. Core Team and ECO Nets to provide input BEFORE you establish a contract and develop a scope of work to ensure our needs are met and PSP is able to procure enough money to create the site as needed.

column805: Focus on grants is for new projects. Continuity of ongoing projects or sustaining volunteer groups is lost or disrupted by constant focus on new projects. Specific case is Beachwatchers -- there are hundreds of BWs around Puget Sound with thousands of volunteer hours. The Beach Watcher funding was rerouted from WSU through PSP and the funding has fallen off over the last couple years -- because the grant moneys go to new (and sometimes redundant) projects?? because PSP built a large organization?? This lack of funding has created a huge loss in volunteer efforts around the Sound due to PSP's lack of keeping up the commitment to fund Beach Watcher. (In the last 5 years my husband and I volunteered over 1000 hours through Beach Watcher programs -- now they are gone)

column805: I actually think the PSP needs to narrow it's focus on a handful of specific issues that need leadership. Right now PSP sticks its hand in everything but doesn't do anything really well. column805: For me, the HCCC, the appointed LIO for Hood Canal Action Area, is supposedly the "natural" organization and a "model" for other LIOs is not working. There does not appear to be PSP Leadership Council guidelines or performance review standards for what a LIO is to do, how, when. For example, in the latest Action Agenda update, both LHCWC and WRIA 16/14b were told by PSP staff and HCCC that our items were to be submitted thru our LIO, the HCCC. Actions were submitted to HCCC in time and in the appropriate format. None of the actions made it into the document submitted by the LIO/HCCC. The HCCC still does not have an adopted Integrated Watershed Management Plan. The PSP Leadership Council needs to determine and define what an LIO is and what the LIO is supposed to do, develop performance review standards, and, perhaps, every 5 years or so, put out an RFP for organizations to apply to be the appointed LIO.

column805: You could put less of your resources into trying to coordinate the many groups and recognize that we are for the most part working roughly in parallel on different aspects of a very large problem. We could use support in communication, but that is different from coordination. And you could recognize that uplands are connected to the waters of Puget Sound and upland land use decisions are important to the health of the sound. And of course we could use political weight. PSP could help us most by advocating strongly in favor of legislation to support our work rather than hobble it. We liked the agency best when it was the Puget Sound Water Quality Authority. The Sound will not be restored by coordination and cooperation but by exercising authority to change land and water use practices.

column805: Most agency and municipality staff are overworked and overwhelmed with the concurrent staff reductions and increased regulatory requirements and pressures. Dedicated and passionate professionals are passing up opportunities for more involvement or collaboration, because it is just not physically possible to be in multiple places at once or to effectively management the enormous workload being placed upon them when they are frequently travelling and filling up their calendars with meetings. Also, although project/program collaboration in some instances can help "share" a particular work task (such as through grants, ILA's, and so forth), it nearly always comes with excessive project managment and administration such as legal/policy-making body by-in, public by-in, applications, budget & task tracking, and reporting. Yes, all projects have some measure of this, but collaborating with another entity seems to add multiple layers to those tasks. As they have ever been, the political and legal/jurisdictional boundaries on the ground and in legislation makes it nearly impossible to apply funds and resources across jurisdictions and responsibilities. Lastly, the current Clean Water Act and Surface and Stormwater Management Utility - related legislation is so outdated, jurisdictions spend a great deal of time defending the application of SSWM fees and other similar fees to address Clean Water Act requirements, rather than getting the work done. Unfortunately, in some cases, losing the legal battle to use SSWM fees for such purposes (Lewiston, Idaho). It is time to update our legislation to address current needs (such as water and habitat quality assessment and restoration), rather than just flood management and infrastructure maintenance.

column805: Form a forum of LIOs where we can exchange ideas and strategies. As the Alliance for a Healthy South Sound is, by it's nature, a collaborative (4 county, 3 tribe) organization, plus the 30+ stakeholders in our council. I formally consult with those members regularly, under the auspices of our organization. Strategizing, planning etc. with additional organizations is difficult to value as the majority of the local voices are present within the organization itself.
